        "excerpt": "The sower went out to sow his seed... Other seed fell into the good soil, and grew up, and produced a crop a hundred times as great.",
        "body": "Luke opens with a deliberate snapshot: Jesus is itinerating through *city after city, village after village* (8:1), preaching and proclaiming the kingdom, accompanied by the Twelve and by named women — Mary Magdalene, Joanna (wife of Herod's steward Chuza, a Herodian household), Susanna — who *contributed to their support out of their private means* (8:3). Luke uniquely names these women and uniquely tells us that the Galilean ministry was financially underwritten by their generosity. This is a quiet but radical detail. Joanna's connection to Chuza means the ministry was being funded, at least in part, by a woman whose access to wealth came from the household of the very Herod who had executed John the Baptist (9:7-9). The kingdom advance is not a self-sustaining miracle; it is sustained by ordinary disciples who treat their resources as ministry capital.\n\nWhen the crowds gather (8:4), Jesus tells the parable of the Sower. The story is deceptively simple: a sower casts seed; four destinations; three failures; one extravagant success (*a hundred times as great*). The disciples ask what it means (8:9), and Jesus' answer in 8:10 is a hard saying. To them it is *granted* (a passive of divine giving) to *know the mysteries of the kingdom*; to *the rest* the kingdom comes wrapped in parables, *so that seeing they may not see, and hearing they may not understand*. The clause quotes Isaiah 6:9-10 — the commission given Isaiah at his temple vision, where the prophet's preaching would harden the already-hardened. Parabolic teaching, then, is not pedagogical inefficiency; it is judicial. Those whose hearts are already closed receive the word in a form that exposes their closedness; those whose hearts the Father has opened receive the same parable and ask, *what does this mean?* (8:9).\n\nThe interpretation (8:11-15) classifies four soils — and here Luke makes a move that the parable's reputation as a hearing-parable sometimes obscures. *The seed is the word of God* (8:11). The four soils are not four types of people in the abstract; they are four ways the *logos tou theou* is encountered. **Path** (8:12): heard, then immediately removed by the devil, who acts specifically *so that they will not believe and be saved*. This is the chapter's most explicit statement of demonic strategy — the devil's interest is precisely in preventing the connection between hearing and saving faith. **Rocky** (8:13): received *with joy*, but without root; belief lasts *pros kairon* (for a season), and *in the season of testing* (*en kairō peirasmou*) it falls away (*aphistantai* — the verb behind English *apostasy*). The two *kairos* phrases bracket the verse: superficial joy lasts only as long as the gap before testing arrives. **Thorny** (8:14): heard but choked by three specified weeds — *merimnai* (worries), *ploutos* (riches), *hēdonai tou biou* (pleasures of this life). The verb *telesphoreō* (bear fruit *to maturity*) is rare and exact: the issue is not that no fruit forms, but that it never matures. The thorny-soil hearer has spiritual activity that never ripens. **Good** (8:15): heard *en kardia kalē kai agathē* (in a noble and good heart), held fast (*katechousin*), and bearing fruit *en hupomonē* (with perseverance — the same word James uses for endurance under trial).\n\nThe pastoral force of the parable rests on its diagnostic specificity. Each failure mode names a real spiritual mechanism: demonic interference, lack of depth, competing affections. The success mode names not technique but a *kind of heart* — one that holds the word fast and lets time and trial prove its fruit. Luke 8 does not let the reader stay neutral. Either the word is being snatched, withering, choked, or maturing. There is no fifth category. The question the parable forces is which of the four describes the last six months of your engagement with Scripture, prayer, and church.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Logos tou theou* — the word of God — is Luke's standard term for the gospel proclamation; the same phrase recurs at 8:21 closing the section. *Peirasmos* (8:13) and *merimna / ploutos / hēdonē* (8:14) are clinical labels for the trial-pressure and competing-affection mechanisms by which hearts that received the word fail to bear fruit. *Hupomonē* (8:15) is steady endurance under sustained pressure — the same Pauline / Jacobean virtue."
